`toThreadSafeSlice` in `src/string.zig` is the ownership root of the crash path: the async thread-safe branch (`tag == .WTFStringImpl`, `slice.allocator.isNull()`) does two `this.ref()` calls while returning a `SliceWithUnderlyingString` that is later converted to JS via `transferToJS`. In that flow, `StringOrBuffer.toJS` calls `transferToJS`, which routes into `BunString__transferToJS` and performs a C++-side `impl.wtf->deref()` before nulling the BunString, while the Zig-side `SliceWithUnderlyingString.deinit()` also does `underlying.deref()`. Under long-lived async/worked-thread traffic this leads to a double-drop pattern on the shared `WTFStringImpl`, producing refcount corruption (`panic(main thread): switch on corrupt value`) and eventual memory-growth/corruption symptoms.

ROOTCAUSE: src/string.zig::toThreadSafeSlice
FIX: In the thread-safe ASCII fast path, keep the retained ownership count consistent with exactly one C++ transfer-drop plus one Zig teardown-drop (typically by removing one of the two `this.ref()` calls or pairing it with a matching non-transfer ownership contract), then ensure both branches consume refs through one well-defined release path.
